article.description: With the game on the line, Notre Dame turned to its senior leaders to help the sixth-ranked Fighting Irish avoid an upset by unranked Southern California.
article.headline: Irish have defeated the Women of Troy six of last seven times
article.linkText: Duffy, Batteast help Irish avoid upset at USC
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- With the game on the line, Notre Dame turned
to its senior leaders to help the sixth-ranked Fighting Irish avoid
an upset by unranked Southern California.

Point guard Megan Duffy and forward Jacqueline Batteast helped
rally the undefeated Irish to a 60-56 victory over USC on Friday.

Duffy made two driving layups and four free throws over the
course of the game's final 8 minutes and Batteast added a bank shot
and a layup that sparked a 10-0 run, which turned a 45-40 deficit
into a 50-45 lead for the Irish (6-0).

Jamie Funn led USC (1-2) with 13 points and Shay Murphy and Kim
Gipson added 12 apiece for the Women of Troy.

"We had stretches where we had a lot of freshmen and sophomores
on the floor," Notre Dame coach Muffet McGraw said. "Our veteran
players didn't play a very good game until the end, except for
Megan Duffy."

Duffy scored 10 of her 12 points in the second half; Batteast
scored 12 of her 18 points in the first half and made just 7 of 20
shots.

Reserve Crystal Erwin added 9 points in 19 minutes for Notre
Dame, which was playing its first road game of the season.

The Irish defeated the Women of Troy for the sixth time in seven
meetings. Notre Dame has won three straight against USC in Los
Angeles. USC's last victory over an opponent ranked as high as
Notre Dame was a 59-56 win last Jan. 25 against Stanford, which was
ranked No. 6 at the time.

"I think you have to give USC credit," Duffy said. "It was
our first road game and, I don't know, maybe we had the jitters.
Finally, we settled down and played Notre Dame basketball."

McGraw said the Irish relied too often on Batteast to score.

"We put too much of a burden on Jackie," McGraw said. "It was
like we were saying, 'Save us, save us.' Our post game has to get a
lot better. It's our No. 1 concern and taking better care of the
ball is No. 2."

Mark Trakh, USC's first-year coach, said he believed his team
outplayed the Irish.

USC made just 7 of 17 free throws, but out-rebounded Notre Dame,
42-36, including by 18-7 on the offensive boards.

"We should have won the game," Trakh said. "We make our free
throws and we win the game. We outplayed them. We out-rebounded
them. We played great defense."
